                        <interp inst="t18431023-name-1554" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431023-name-1554" type="surname" value="WILKS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431023-name-1554" type="given" value="JOSEPH BARBER"></interp>JOSEPH BARBER WILKS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am cashier to the East India Company, and live at No. 1, Pleasant-place, Camberwell. In the early part of Sept., I was stopping with my family at Ramsgate—I saw Mr. Bridgman there on the 5th of Sept.—I went on the pier with my family, and met Mr. Bridgman unexpectedly, just arrived by the boat—I it was about five, but I cannot state—I did not see him land, but met him on the pier among the people, who then landed from the boat, which came from London—I went</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184310230217"></xptr>
               <p>up and shook hands with him, having known him some years, and having a very great respect for him, I said, "Mr. Bridgman, I see you are alone, come home with me," and he accompanied me home with my family—I was living at No. 10, Camden-place—he took tea with us on the 5th, on his ar<lb></lb>rival, and took supper the same evening—I invited him to make my house his home, consequently he breakfasted on the following morning (Wednes<lb></lb>day) dined, took tea, and supped on Wednesday, leaving my house from half past ten till eleven—he breakfasted on Thursday—he did not dine, but took tea, and supped on Thursday, breakfasted and dined on Friday, and on Friday afternoon I and my family accompanied him to the pier, and saw him on board the Dover packet about six o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What time did you dine on Wednesday? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> We generally dined about two o'clock—we took tea about six—I think he did not stay at home the rest of the evening—he merely took his meals with me—he told me at supper that he had been to chapel—he went out after tea, and re<lb></lb>turned in the evening, I cannot say at what time, perhaps about nine—he told me the text, and the particulars.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you remember the text? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, it was "Fear not to go down into Egypt, I will go with thee"—or something of that sort, relat<lb></lb>ing to Joseph and his brethren, I think, but I am not quite clear at this moment—he told me the text at the time, and it was rather a remarkable one.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BODKIN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long have you known him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Ten or twelve years, and always considered him a most excellent man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you ever visit at his house? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I have called, and have seen one female servant there—the younger prisoner is his only grown up son—there are three children altogether—-the others are quite children, not old enough to be witnesses—I know the days on which I saw Mr. Bridgman to be the 5th, 6th, and 7th, because I went down on the 23rd of Aug., and had been there a fortnight all but a day—my eldest son was to have come down to spend the last week—I intended remaining four weeks, but the weather being exceedingly fine I wrote to him at the end of the second week to come down a week earlier, and he came down on the 5th, the day Mr. Bridgman did—he is not here—I have a letter here which he wrote on the Monday, saying that he should come down the following day if fine—here is the post-mark of 4th Sept. on it—on the front is the Walworth post-mark, and on the other part is the Ramsgate post-mark of the 5th Sept.—he says on the outside, "I intend coming down to-morrow"—he dined and drank tea with Mr. Bridgman as well as myself.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431023-name-1555" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431023-name-1555" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431023-name-1555" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431023-name-1555" type="given" value="EDWARD MASON"></interp>EDWARD MASON THOMPSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the son of Mr. Thompson, who has been examined—I was with him at Ramsgate in Sept.—I know Mr. Bridg<lb></lb>man, and saw him at Ramsgate on Thursday the 7th of Sept., between one and two o'clock, on the pier with my father.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">GEORGE GARFORD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You state that this occurred on Wed<lb></lb>nesday the 6th, what fixes the day in your mind? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I can scarcely say what can bring it to my remembrance now—I know I was with Mr. Tawney on the following Monday.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431023-name-1556" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431023-name-1556" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431023-name-1556" type="surname" value="COLSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431023-name-1556" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN COLSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an officer of Guy's Hospital. The younger defen<lb></lb>dant has been a student of surgery there for some time, and had the charac<lb></lb>ter of an assiduous, zealous student.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">J. W. BRIDGMAN</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18431023-3104-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
